04792nam a22007335i 9780801460760DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979968133  a97808014607607 a10.7591/97808014607602doi  a(DE-B1597)478301  a(OCoLC)732957159  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR418.P3bH55 2016 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a820.93582097342231 aHiltner, Ken, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Else Is Pastoral? :bRenaissance Literature and the Environment /cKen Hiltner. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Literary Issues -- t1. The Nature of Art -- t2. What Else Is Pastoral? -- t3. What Else Was Pastoral in the Renaissance? -- t4. Pastoral and Ideology, and the Environment -- tPart II. Environmental Problems -- t5. Representing Air Pollution in Early Modern London -- t6. Environmental Protest Literature of the Renaissance -- t7. Empire, the Environment, and the Growth of Georgic -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPastoral was one of the most popular literary forms of early modern England. Inspired by classical and Italian Renaissance antecedents, writers from Ben Jonson to John Beaumont and Abraham Cowley wrote in idealized terms about the English countryside. It is often argued that the Renaissance pastoral was a highly figurative mode of writing that had more to do with culture and politics than with the actual countryside of England. For decades now literary criticism has had it that in pastoral verse, hills and crags and moors were extolled for their metaphoric worth, rather than for their own qualities. In What Else Is Pastoral?, Ken Hiltner takes a fresh look at pastoral, offering an environmentally minded reading that reconnects the poems with literal landscapes, not just figurative ones.Considering the pastoral in literature from Virgil and Petrarch to Jonson and Milton, Hiltner proposes a new ecocritical approach to these texts. We only become truly aware of our environment, he explains, when its survival is threatened. As London expanded rapidly during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, the city and surrounding rural landscapes began to look markedly different. Hiltner finds that Renaissance writers were acutely aware that the countryside they had known was being lost to air pollution, deforestation, and changing patterns of land use; their works suggest this new absence of nature through their appreciation for the scraps that remained in memory or in fact. A much-needed corrective to the prevailing interpretation of pastoral poetry, What Else Is Pastoral? shows the value of reading literature with an ecological eye.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEcology in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aNature in literature. 0aPastoral literature, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aEnvironmental History. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146076040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460760/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL